# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: burmese-cuisine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The **1962 Burmese coup d'état** marked the beginning of one-party rule in Burma (Myanmar) and the political dominance of the military in Burmese politics.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In the 2 March 1962 coup, the military replaced the civilian AFPFL-government headed by Prime Minister U Nu with the Union Revolutionary Council Chaired by General Ne Win.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In the first 12 years following the coup, the country was ruled under martial law, and saw a significant expansion in the military's role in the national economy, politics, and state bureaucracy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Following the constitution of 1974, the Revolutionary Council handed over the power to the elected government, consisting of a single-party, the Burma Socialist Programme Party, which had been founded by the council in 1962.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The military junta retained power for 23 years until 2011, when it was transferred to the Union Solidarity and Development Party.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] After the end of the Second World War and Burma's independence in 1948, Burma became a democratic socialist country and joined the Non-Aligned Movement.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The elected Prime Minister U Nu appointed Ne Win as Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces, on 1 February 1949, and was given total control of the army, replacing General Smith Dun, an ethnic Karen.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] However, the degraded economy and social disorder placed emphasis on the military.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In October 1958, when instability in society rose to a level approaching a national security crisis, the civilian government and Prime Minister U Nu asked the military and Ne Win to step in as a temporary caretaker government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Once the political order had been restored, the caretaker government was expected to execute general elections and restore civilian rule.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Public support for the army was strengthened after the army facilitated the 1960 elections and acknowledged the authority of the elected civil government Anti-Fascist People's Freedom League (AFPFL), led by U Nu.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Yet the general public continued to perceive the elected government as corrupt, inept at ruling the country, and unable to restore law and order in a Burmese society characterised by ever-increasing crime rates.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The military continued to be perceived as crucial to ensuring social stability, which was a high priority among the Burmese people following years of colonialism and World War II.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Less than two years after the caretaker government had handed power back to the AFPFL-government, on 2 March 1962, Ne Win again seized power in a military-staged coup d'état.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Before the coup, Samaduwa Sinhwanaung, Chief Minister of Kachin State and close ally with Prime Minister U Nu, was designated as president for next 5 years by Union Parliament on 28 February 1962.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] However he did not take office because of the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Ne Win became head of state as Chairman of the *Union Revolutionary Council* and also Prime Minister.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] He arrested U Nu, Sao Shwe Thaik, and several others, and declared a socialist state run by a "Revolutionary Council" of senior military officers.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Sao Shwe Thaik's son, Sao Mye Thaik, who was 17 at the time, was shot dead in what was generally described as a "bloodless" coup by the world's media.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Thibaw Sawbwa Sao Kya Seng also disappeared mysteriously after being stopped at a checkpoint near Taunggyi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Following riots at Rangoon University in July 1962, troops were sent to restore order.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] They fired on protesters and destroyed the student union building.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] All universities were closed for more than two years until September 1964.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In 1988, 26 years later, Ne Win denied any involvement in the dynamiting of the Student Union building, stating that his deputy Brigadier Aung Gyi, who he had fallen out with and dismissed by that time, had given the order to dynamite the building.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Ne Win further stated that he himself, as a "revolutionary leader", had to take responsibility for the incident by giving the "sword with sword and spear with spear" speech.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Due to the AFPFL-government's weak position in society, the coup was not unexpected, and Ne Win had been urged to seize power by members of the army.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Several foreign governments considered the military takeover a logical, if not positive, development.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The coup was executed with the arrest of Prime Minister U Nu, five other cabinet members, the Chief of Justice, and around thirty politicians and former leaders from the states of Shan and Kayah.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Only one person was killed, the son of general Sao Shwe Thaik, which is why the coup has been described as bloodless.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The descriptions of the coup vary in the scholarly literature, when it comes to how militarily coordinated the coup was.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Taylor, Ne Win assumed power in secrecy, without the knowledge of even the deputy commander of the armed forced, Brigadier General Aung Gyi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Just 28 officers were involved in the operation, and only Ne Win knew the date of the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In fact, Callahan argues that the coup illustrated that the military acted as a united, bureaucratised entity, and that it might be this unity that explains the durability of the authoritarian rule that followed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] There have been various explanations to why the military, headed by Ne Win, staged the military coup less than two years after acknowledging the authority of the civilian government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] A reason, which is highlighted by multiple historians, is that the coup was a response to a growing fear within the army that the Union of Burma was drifting towards disintegration under the AFPFL-Government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] This explanation resonates with the one given by the army in the official press release following the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] By 1962 the integrity of the country was seen as threatened by the two minorities, the Shan and Kayah, who were claiming their right, given by the 1947 constitution, to withdraw from the Union.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] On top of this the Shan leaders were beginning to form an armed opposition against Yangon to claim Shan "*national determination*".
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The army and Ne Win saw it as their responsibility to protect the cohesion of the Union and in the official press release the coup was presented as a necessity due to the policies of the AFPFL-government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Especially problematic was U Nu's attempt to make Buddhism the state religion, since it contributed to the Christian minorities' motivation to fight for autonomy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Furthermore, the army believed that the federal system and parliament-style government was inherently weak and encouraged local autonomy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The multiple voices represented in parliament were seen as evoking instability and enhancing ethnic differences that would bring down the Union.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The army thus argued that there was a need for a strong central government to secure the integration of the nation.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Additionally, the military rule justified the abolition of the political system by saying that multi-party democracy served the wealthy in society in being open to politicians representing capitalists and landlords.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] This critique of the political system served both as a reason for conducting the coup but also as a justification of the state structures and policies that were implemented in the subsequent years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The increased autonomy in peripheral areas was also seen as problematic in terms of external threats.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The army believed that if the areas got too independent they would attract foreign powers – a risk that seemed great with the Cold War context of 1962.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In 1962 it was clear that the United States had a great interest in Asian countries bordering communist powers, which meant that Burma was a possible subject of interest with the country's borders to China.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] If the union dissolved and the Shan and Kayah States claimed autonomy it meant that the states could pursue independent foreign policy and engage in alliances with powerful states like the United States.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Due to the international security status an alliance like this would create a significant security threat to the rest of the country, with an increased risk of a conflict between the United States and China on Burmese territory.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Furthermore, the regional context served as argument to prevent the union from dissolving.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The instability of divided Vietnam and Laos underlined the need to retain central control with the frontier states.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In this scenario of external threats and an internal threat of disintegration, the civilian government was perceived as inadequate to protect the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Additionally, personal rivalry in the government damaged the cohesion and the power of the already weak AFPFL.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In turn, Ne Win and the army feared that a split in the party would induce further instability.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] This fear was enhanced when U Nu announced that he would not run for office in the following election, which in turn increased the incentive to stage the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Historians differ when it comes to the importance of Ne Win as an individual leader in explaining why the coup was established and successfully executed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Aung Thwin & Aung Thwin argue that Ne Win possessed political legitimacy founded in Burmese culture and history, which enabled him to seize power in the 1962 coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Ne Win's political credentials were based on his fighting for the country in the 1940s and the fact that he served as a trusted lieutenant to Aung San, who was considered to be a national hero.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In contrast Callahan argues that neither the specific character of Ne Win nor the threat of disintegration were the decisive causes for the staging of the coup, since these factors were present throughout the 1950s, without them leading to an army intervention.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Instead Callahan suggests that the coup was a result of inter-elite conflicts over the state structures, and who possessed the legitimate claim on the state.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The consolidation of the military was a result of lengthy periods of wars, as well as intra-military struggles, which led to a purge of army commanders who had tense relationships with Ne Win.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In this way Callahan argues that Ne Win seized power at a time where there were no genuine obstacles due to the strong character of the military.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Immediately after the coup Ne Win and a number of senior military officers formed the Revolutionary Council, which consisted of sixteen senior military officers and Ne Win as the council's chairman.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Furthermore, the Revolutionary Government Cabinet was established with eight senior military officers from the council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The aim of Revolution Council was to lead an anti-colonial revolution and reassert the state.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Revolutionary council replaced the AFPFL-government and the day after the establishing of the new governmental body, the council abolished fundamental state institutions established with the 1947 constitution.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] This included the two houses of the Hluttaw (the parliament), the central legislature and the regional councils – the channel of communication from the ethnic states to Yangon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The bureaucratic power embedded in these institutions was transferred to the Revolutionary Council and Ne Win.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The concentration of power in the hands of Ne Win continued on 5 March 1962 when he undertook all executive, legislate and judicial authority by virtue of being the Chairman of the Revolutionary Council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] As head of both the Revolutionary Council and the Revolutionary Government Cabinet Taylor argues that: "...
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The Revolutionary Council's political dominance was further ensured by making all institutions that were not eliminated by law dependent on the council either through their personnel or through finances, which prevented them from organising any opposition.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The coup created a policy vacuum, where the Revolutionary Council and Ne Win could realise their ideas for society, but Ne Win needed a rationale for implementing his political agenda that would resonate with the population.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] This led to the formulation of the Burmese Way to Socialism, which was presented to the public on 7 May 1962.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The state ideology The Burmese Way to Socialism had the aim of centralising the economy and limiting foreign influence on businesses.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The anti-communist military resorting to a leftist ideology was perceived as surprising by external agents.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Myoe the inclusion of Marxism strengthened and prolonged the political dominance of the army, since it enabled the neutralisation of the communism, while projecting the army as revolutionary institution that could ensure the population's socialists' demands.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In a security perspective the leftist state ideology furthermore minimised the risk of Chinese attacks, which in 1962 constituted the largest external threat to Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] To secure public support of the ideology the Marxist elements were supplemented with Buddhist concepts to create ideological objectives that were compatible with the morals of the country's Buddhist majority.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The socialism applied thus became a localised version, fitted to the Burmese identity.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The priorities in the ideological framework were the establishing of a socialist economy and the interests of the peasants, who comprised the largest group in society, and potentially the biggest threat to the government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] To distinguish the Burmese Way to Socialism from communism, Ne Win argued that the socialist system of Burma should benefit all people of society and that the business class was not seen as the enemy, as long as they supported the Revolutionary Council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In this sense the objective was a national social revolution across classes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] However, since the peasants made up the largest group in society and since this class was perceived as having been neglected under colonial rule as well as by the post-colonial governments, policies to improve the economy and conditions of peasants were prioritised.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Furthermore, it was believed that by focusing on the peasants in terms of a coherent social class rather than ethnicity the integration of society could be improved.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The notion of ethnicity should be neutralised by developing new community affiliations based on a national cultural identity and a shared public history founded in a Buddhist past.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The implementation of the new ideology was Leninist in its implementation, in the sense that the Revolutionary Council wanted to form a single, legal political party through which all participatory processes would take place.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In a meeting on 17 May between the revolutionary council and the civilian party leaders, the leaders announced that they would not participate in establishing a single political party and refused to endorse the Burmese Way to Socialism.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] According to Taylor it has been debated if the party leaders thought the military would eventually give up its power to the civilian parties, like they had done following the elections in 1960.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] It has also been suggested that the AFPFL may have expected that the military would, in one way or another, share power with the party, whom it had cooperated with prior to the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] With the rejection of the civilian parties to conform to the Burmese Way of Socialism, the Revolutionary Council began the building of a party consisting of the political elite, and on 4 July 1962 the Burma Socialist Programme Party (BSPP) was presented.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] All remaining parties were banned by law.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Initially the BSPP was only made up by members of the Revolutionary Council but eventually it also attracted politicians, especially the left-oriented.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Furthermore, Ne Win included civil servants and former politicians who were ready to conform to the military rule in the BSPP.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Aung Thwin and Aung Thwin argue that the inclusion of individuals, who were a part of the previous administration, is a trait that can be seen in the behaviour of Burmese Kings prior to the colonial rule.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The kings used ministers that have served under previous royal opponents.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Aung Thwin and Aung Thwin thus suggest that this strategy of engaging people from the former administration in the new political organs is an indigenous historical feature in Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The opportunity to be a part of BSPP was especially popular among the people, who had been kept outside the power elite of the AFPFL-government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The objective of the BSPP was to be the main channel for participation and mobilisation of people to support the state.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The political orientation of the BSPP was described as the middle way between social democracy and communism, and the party should represent all working people.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Thus the party was conceived as an alternative to the parties, which made up the previous governments and was categorised in terms of being either right or left oriented.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] By claiming to represent all the people the party also aimed at distinguishing itself from communism, which formed an opposition to the landlords and capitalists.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In the first decade following the formation of the BSPP the revolutionary council enjoyed the supremacy over the party.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] This was in accordance with the party's constitution, which stated that he Revolutionary Council was "*the supreme authority of the party during the transitional period of its construction*".
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] This hierarchy should later be reversed so the BSPP would lead the Revolutionary Council, and in 1974 with the formation of a new constitution the party took the political leadership in the general elections.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Multiple scholars, including Aung Thwin & Aung Thwin and Taylor, describe how the coup at first didn't affect the lives of the general population in Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] To the majority of the population who worked in agriculture the coup initially improved the living conditions due to the military regime's egalitarian politics which prioritised the peasant.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] One obvious change for people, though, was that the new power elite would consist of army generals and the channel to obtain status was a military career.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Furthermore, no foreign powers opposed the coup since the Revolutionary Council reassured that Myanmar's foreign policy of neutrality in the Cold War would continue.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Despite the limited immediate implication for society at large the military coup resulted in comprehensive societal changes in the subsequent years with the Revolutionary Council's implementation of their policies founded in the Burmese Way to Socialism.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] As stated above the coup resulted in the abolition of the 1947 constitution, which eliminated major state institutions and concentrated the power in the Revolutionary Council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Furthermore, the military implemented secular policies and broke the tradition of cooperation with the Buddha Sasana Council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] To re-establish what was considered the indigenous Burmese culture and to distinguish the country from its colonial past it became a political objective to move away from values and culture that was considered foreign and external.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Concretely the government made Burmese the official language of the Union – as opposed to English.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Other initiatives were the promotion of Burmese literature and the changing of street names that referred to prominent British individuals into names of famous Burmese persons.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Even Western funding programmes such as the Fulbright scholarship programmes were shut down to ensure that no channels of external influence remained.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] These policies continue to have implications in Burma today, where English is spoken to a very narrow degree in the general public.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Burma also turned away from the outside world when it came to the economic policies.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The Burmanization of the economy included the expulsion of many Chinese and Indians from the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Ne Win's government prohibited foreigners from owning land and practicing certain professions.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] By the mid-1960s Myanmar's foreign trade declined and the ratio of foreign trade to GDP declined from 40 per cent in 1960 to 26 per cent in 1970.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The economic policies focused on realising the objective of creating a socialist economy, but initially the question of the nationalisation of the economy constituted a point of conflict within the Revolutionary Council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] On 24 April the council met for a two-day meeting to discuss the Burmese Way of Socialism in detail before publishing the statement, and the issue which caused the most negotiations was the question of nationalisation.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] On 1 January 1963 the Burmese oil industry was nationalised, but only when council member Aung Gyi, who had been pro private businesses, resigned on 8 February 1963 did a comprehensive nationalisation of both foreign and domestic trade as well as the manufacturing and banking sector begin.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] By March 1964 – two years after the coup – the main part of Myanmar's economy was nationalised.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Due to the Burmese Way to Socialism's focus on improving the lives of the peasants the government chose to prioritise agriculture over industry and manufacturing by initiating policies that directed investment and resources towards the agricultural sector.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] But during the 26 years of military rule this shift in focus away from the industrial sector had great repercussion for the Burmese economy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] By the mid-1980s the neglect of the industrial sector and policies of protecting the peasants from over-taxation and land-seizure meant that the state had limited ability to generate capital to maintain even the most basic services in society.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Despite promising the opposite the government demonetised the kyat in 1985 which damaged the public trust in the government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The combination of the demonetisation and the drop in the price of rice and timber severely harmed the population and the agrarian economy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] People began taking money out of the banks as yet another demonetisation occurred, which resulted in protests amongst the urban population.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] The economic downturn meant that the state could not pay its foreign loans, which led to the UN's categorisation of Burma as the Least Developed Country in 1987.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] According to Taylor, the lack of economic and democratic development in Burma during the 26 years of military rule under Ne Win resulted in the uprising of 1988, where people in a nationwide demonstration opposed the military dominance in the name of democracy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Different aspects of the coup can be highlighted as significant depending on how the historical events following the coup are being read and analysed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] A common understanding of the coup is the framing of the coup and the decades that followed as a period of autocracy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] In this narrative the significance of the coup becomes the military's ability to retain power and suppress democratisation for 26 years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Callahan describes the period that follows the coup as one characterised by significant military presence in society.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Another narrative can be characterised as cosmopolitan and frames the significance of the coup in terms of the following isolation from the international society and disconnectedness due to the state's economic and cultural detachment from the outside.
[src:burmese-cuisine/1962-burmese-coup-d-état] Within this narrative the significance of the coup is the genuine independence and autonomy that it facilitated.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The **2011–2015 Myanmar political reforms** were a series of political, economic and administrative reforms in Myanmar undertaken by the military-backed government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] As a consequence of the reforms, ASEAN approved Myanmar's bid for the chairmanship in 2014.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] United States Secretary of State Hillary Clinton visited Myanmar on 1 December 2011, to encourage further progress; it was the first visit by a Secretary of State in more than fifty years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] United States President Barack Obama visited one year later, becoming the first US president to visit the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Aung San Suu Kyi's party, the National League for Democracy, participated in by-elections held on 1 April 2012 after the government abolished laws that led to the NLD's boycott of the 2010 general election.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] She led the NLD in winning the by-elections in a landslide, winning 41 out of 44 of the contested seats, with Aung San Suu Kyi herself winning a seat representing Kawhmu Constituency in the lower house of the Myanmar Parliament.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] However, uncertainties existed as some other political prisoners have not been released and clashes between Myanmar troops and local insurgent groups continued.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In 2021, the reforms were rolled back in the aftermath of the 2021 Myanmar coup d'état and outbreak of civil war.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Burma was under military rule from 1962 to 2010.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In 2008, the ruling Junta, State Peace and Development Council, announced the new constitution as a part of roadmap to democracy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The constitution, which reserves 25% of the Hluttaw legislature's seats for military, is seen by the opposition as a tool for continuing military control of the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] A constitution referendum was held in 2008 amid Cyclone Nargis.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Observers criticised the referendum for voter intimidation, electoral fraud and advance voting.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Nevertheless, on 15 May 2008, the junta announced that the constitution had been approved by 92.4% of voters, claiming a 99% turnout in the two-thirds of the region that had held the vote.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The military backed Union Solidarity and Development Party declared victory.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The United Nations and Western countries expressed concerns about the conduct of the elections.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Nevertheless, the government has embarked reforms toward liberal democracy, mixed economy, and reconciliation, although the motives of such reforms are still debated.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The law will be effective 1 April 2012, when the 2012 Burmese by-elections take place.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Two days later, the Ministry of Mines announced that it would file a lawsuit against the journal.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The pro-democracy leader, Aung San Suu Kyi was released from house arrest on 13 November 2010.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] After her release, she held a series of dialogues with President Thein Sein and Minister Aung Kyi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Aung San Suu Kyi's party, National League for Democracy boycotted the 2010 election.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The election law enacted by the SPDC did not allow ex-prisoners to become members of registered political parties.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] If NLD decided to register, it would have to expel its members who were imprisoned.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] But in November, the government erased the clause in a parliamentary section.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] After the amendments, NLD leaders have unanimously decided to register for the by-election.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The government has relaxed press and internet censorship laws, for example allowing photographs of Aung San Suu Kyi to be published on the front page of local newspapers.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Tint Swe, the head of the country's censorship authority, the Press Scrutiny and Registration Division, said that censorship is incompatible with democratic practices and should be abolished.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] A presidential adviser has indicated that press censorship will be abolished in 2012 under new media legislation.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In September 2011, several banned websites including YouTube, Democratic Voice of Burma and Voice of America have been unblocked.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In January 2012, the Ministry of Information announced that it had forwarded a draft of a new media and press law to the Attorney General's Office for review.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The draft law, which will need to be approved by the Pyidaungsu Hluttaw (National Parliament), borrows some language from similar laws in Cambodia, Indonesia and Vietnam.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The draft law, which is adapted from the 1962 Printers and Publishers Registration Law, will not be submitted during the second parliamentary session.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] On a similar note, Yi Htut, the Information and Public Relations Division's Director-General stated that the new media law would avoid the extremes of the past, outline journalists' rights and responsibilities and that he was in consultation with UNESCO experts with regard to the new law.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The government has convened an independent National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) consisting of 15 retired bureaucrats and academics.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Analysts have questioned the panel's will and ability to challenge the government, but the commission has challenged the President's claims that there are no political prisoners in Myanmar, calling for all political prisoners' release.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Two general amnesties were held in 2011 releasing between 10,000 and 40,000 prisoners, although only about 300 of them are considered political prisoners by monitor groups such as the Assistance Association for Political Prisoners (AAPP).
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] After the second general amnesty, some prominent prisoners of conscience such as comedian Zarganar have been released, while others such as 8888 Uprising leader Min Ko Naing remained in prison.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The government also approved the NHRC's suggestion to relocate political prisoners so that their family members can easily contact them.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] There are varying definitions of "political prisoner", but Amnesty International and the NLD consider Myanmar to have 600 political prisoners.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] As of March 2012, various organisations have identified upwards of 619 remaining political prisoners (AAP has identified 413) in jail.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] As of April 2013, according to Assistance Association for Political Prisoners, there are currently 176 political prisoners, in Burmese prisons.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] On 23 July 2013, another amnesty was announced and 73 political prisoners were released, but about 100 political prisoners were still remained.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In October 2011, the government passed new International Labour Organization-approved legislation that allows for labour unions with at least 30 members, the right to strike, given 2 weeks' notice.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] This law, effective 9 March 2012, also provides for punishment of employers who dismiss workers on strike or unionised workers with up to a year in prison and a fine of 100,000 kyat, as well punishment of workers who stage illegal strikes, with up to a year in jail and a fine of 30,000 kyat.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] On 16 March 2012, the Ministry of Labour signed a memorandum of understanding with the ILO to end forced labour by 2015.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The government has however, denied the presence of other human right issues such as alleged army abuses against ethnic minorities, claiming that in ethnic areas, only local insurgent groups violate human rights.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The government has accused the Kachin Independence Army of planting bombs, destroying bridges and trading in illegal drugs.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Insurgent groups have resumed fighting since a 2008 ceasefire in opposition to the new constitution of Myanmar that requires all armed forces be under the control of the national Defense Service.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Peace talks were held in November to reach a compromise.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Since 2011, Myanmar embarked on policy reforms of anti-corruption laws, currency exchange rates, foreign investment laws and taxation.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Foreign investment increased from US$300 million in 2009–10 to a US$20 billion in 2010–11.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The large inflow of capital resulted in a stronger valuation of the kyat (Burmese currency) by about 25%.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In response, the government relaxed import restrictions and abolished export taxes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Despite currency problems, the Burmese economy was expected to grow by about 8.8% in 2011.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Myanmar has a complex foreign exchange system with black markets, foreign exchange certificates, and multiple exchange rates.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] On request of the government to alleviate its souring currency conditions, an International Monetary Fund (IMF) team visited Myanmar in October.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] After the visit, the government allowed private banks to engage in the foreign exchange market.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The Central Bank of Myanmar embarked on a plan to unify the country's multiple exchange rate system.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] From April 2012 to April 2013, the official exchange rate of 6.4 kyats to US$1 (a rate unchanged since 1977, when it was pegged to the IMF's special drawing rights) was floated up, to foster an interbank money market.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] From 2013 to 2014, the most widely used informal black market rate was anticipated to be eliminated.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The informal exchange rates were used for most daily transactions, while the overvalued official exchange rate was used to calculate government revenue and state-owned enterprises.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] There are other informal exchange rates, such an exchange rate used by UN agencies and international NGOs (450 kyat to US$1 in 2010), a customs rate, and an official market rate.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Such discrepancies distorted national accounts (since firms were required to report all transactions in Burmese kyat at the official rate) and reduced transparency and accountability.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] On 2 April 2012, the Central Bank of Myanmar began trading at the new reference exchange rate of 818 kyat to 1 US dollar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In March 2012, a draft foreign investment law emerged, the first in more than two decades.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] This law would oversee unprecedented liberalisation of the economy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Foreigners would no longer require a local partner to start a business in the country, because they will be able to legally lease land.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The draft law also stipulated that Burmese citizens must constitute at least 25% of the firm's skilled workforce, and with training, increased in increments of 25% up to 75% in subsequent years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Although the government has been applauded for the reforms, many countries remain "cautiously optimistic".
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Japan resumed sending aid which was suspended after the 2007 killing of a Japanese journalist.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] ASEAN approved Burma's bid for chair in 2014.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The United States, Australia and the EU have called for further action, such as the unconditional release of all political prisoners, as a prerequisite for the lifting of international sanctions on the Myanmar government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The United States appointed a special envoy, Derek Mitchell, to chart a new policy from Myanmar away from isolation.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Following the government reforms in 2011 and the visit of U.S.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton to the country, the U.S. announced several initiatives, including the removal of some curbs on foreign aid, aimed at re-engagement with Myanmar, a step toward the restoration of full diplomatic relations.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In January 2012, following the release of prominent political prisoners including Min Ko Naing, the U.S. and Myanmar restored full diplomatic relations and exchanged ambassadors, though further ties would be dependent on additional reforms.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In September 2016, the Cardin-McCain Burma Strategy Act of 2016, a piece of bipartisan proposed U.S. legislation, was introduced to the Senate.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The legislation seeks to set "'benchmarks and guidelines' on sanctions relief by calling on the U.S.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Experts caution that the reforms will be disproved by the hardliners and probably lead to counterrevolution.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] But, Minister U Kyaw Hsan said there is no intention to retract reforms.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The motives of such reforms are also debated.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Marie Lall, a BBC South Asia analyst attributed Burma's bid for the ASEAN chair in 2014, the need to reform the economy for the ASEAN Free Trade Area and the government's desire to win the election in 2015 as the main motives of the reforms.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] In Freedom House's 2012 Freedom in the World, the country's civil liberties rating improved from 7 to 6, because of increased public discussion and news and politics media coverage, and reduced restrictions on education.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Scholar Thant Myint-U has observed that military representatives and MPs have not necessarily voted on party lines on important issues, noting that party organisations are still relatively undeveloped.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Human Rights Watch has criticised a new assembly law, the Law Relating to Peaceful Assembly and Peaceful Procession, signed on 2 December 2011, for restricting the right to protest and failing to meet international standards.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The law requires would-be protesters to seek permission from township police five days in advance, including such details on the demonstration as the slogans to be used, and gives authority arbitrary powers to deny citizens the right to protest.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] Regarding the 2012 by-elections, the National League for Democracy has pointed out irregularities in voter lists, rule violations by local election committees and vote-buying practices by the Union Solidarity and Development Party.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] The country still lacks an independent judiciary system, which remains politicised and closely tied to the government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] For instance, lawyers who defend prisoners of conscience are routinely stripped of their license to practice law, while sentences are arbitrarily administered.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] According to the report, forced labour and military conscription, blockage of international aid, attacks on civilians and private properties, rape and torture, as well as use of landmines, continue to be practised in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2011-2015-myanmar-political-reforms] However, many human rights activists and people in Burma believe that this ethnic hatred is a direct result of military rule, as the military promoted an extreme form of Burman nationalism during the years 1962–2011.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] A coup d'état in Myanmar began on the morning of 1 February 2021, when democratically elected members of the country's ruling party, the National League for Democracy (NLD), were deposed by the Tatmadaw, Myanmar's military, which then vested power in a military junta.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Acting President of Myanmar Myint Swe proclaimed a year-long state of emergency and declared power had been transferred to Commander-in-Chief of Defence Services Senior General Min Aung Hlaing.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] It declared the results of the November 2020 general election invalid and stated its intent to hold a new election at the end of the state of emergency.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The coup d'état occurred the day before the Parliament of Myanmar was to swear in the members elected in the 2020 election, thereby preventing this from occurring.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] President Win Myint and State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi were detained, along with ministers, their deputies, and members of Parliament.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 1 February 2021, Win Myint and Aung San Suu Kyi were arrested on charges that independent analysts regarded as part of an attempt to legitimize the military's seizure of power.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Both were remanded in custody for two weeks.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Between 16 February and 1 April, five additional charges were leveled against Aung San Suu Kyi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Armed insurgencies by the People's Defence Force of the National Unity Government erupted throughout Myanmar in response to the military government's crackdown on anti-coup protests, leading to a multi-sided civil war still ongoing as of 2026.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] As of 13 March 2024, at least 50,000 people, including at least 8,000 civilians (570 of whom were children), have been killed by the junta forces and 26,234 individuals have been arrested.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In March 2021, three prominent members of the National League for Democracy (NLD) died in police custody, and in July 2022, the junta executed four pro-democracy activists.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In honour of the anniversary for Myanmar's 76th year of independence in January 2024, more than 9,000 prisoners are slated to receive amnesty, leading to their release from prison.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In February 2024, it was announced that compulsory military service would be implemented.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] All men aged 18 to 35 and women aged 18 to 27 were required to serve up to two years under military command and specialists such as doctors aged up to 45 were to serve for three years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Myanmar, also known as Burma, has been beset with political instability since it was granted independence from the United Kingdom in January 1948.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Between 1958 and 1960, the military formed a temporary caretaker government at the behest of U Nu, the country's democratically elected prime minister, to resolve political infighting.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The military voluntarily restored civilian government after holding the 1960 Burmese general election.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Less than two years later, the military seized power in the 1962 coup, which under the leadership of General Ne Win, precipitated 26 years of military rule.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In 1988, nationwide protests broke out in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Dubbed the 8888 Uprising, the civil unrest was sparked by economic mismanagement, leading Ne Win to step down.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In September 1988, the military's top leaders formed the State Law and Order Restoration Council (SLORC), which then seized power.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Aung San Suu Kyi, the daughter of General Aung San, the country's founder, became a notable pro-democracy activist during this period.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In 1990, free elections were allowed by the military, under the assumption that the military enjoyed popular support.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Ultimately, the elections resulted in a landslide victory for Aung San Suu Kyi's party, the National League for Democracy (NLD).
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] However, the military refused to cede power and placed her under house arrest.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The military remained in power for another 22 years until 2011, following the military's roadmap to democracy, during which the 2008 Constitution of Myanmar was drafted.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Between 2011 and 2015, a tentative democratic transition began, and elections held in 2015 resulted in a victory for Aung San Suu Kyi's party, the National League for Democracy (NLD).
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] However, the military retained substantial power, including the right to appoint 1⁄4 of all parliament members.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The 2021 coup occurred in the aftermath of the general election on 8 November 2020, in which the NLD won 396 out of 476 seats in parliament, an even larger margin of victory than in the 2015 election.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The military's proxy party, the Union Solidarity and Development Party, won only 33 seats.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The army disputed the results, claiming that the vote was fraudulent.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The coup attempt had been rumored for several days, prompting statements of concern from Western nations such as the United Kingdom, France, the United States, and Australia.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 1 February 2021, NLD spokesman Myo Nyunt said that Aung San Suu Kyi, Win Myint, Han Tha Myint, and other party leaders had been "taken" in an early morning raid.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Myo Nyunt added that he expected to be also detained shortly.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Numerous communications channels stopped working – phone lines to the capital, Naypyidaw, were interrupted, state-run MRTV said it was unable to broadcast due to "technical issues", and widespread Internet disruptions were reported beginning around 3 a.m.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The military disrupted cellular services throughout the country, mirroring "kill switch" tactics previously employed in combat zones in Chin and Rakhine states.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] All the member banks under the Myanmar Banking Association suspended their financial services.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Around 400 elected members of parliament (MPs) were placed under house arrest, confined to a government housing complex in Naypyidaw.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Following the coup, the NLD arranged for the MPs to remain housed in the complex until 6 February.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Social media users began calling on MPs to convene a parliamentary session within a government guesthouse, since the group met the Constitution's quorum requirements.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In response, the military issued another order giving MPs 24 hours to leave the guesthouse premises.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 4 February 70 NLD MPs took an oath of office, in clear defiance of the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] During the coup, soldiers also detained several Buddhist monks who had led the 2007 Saffron Revolution, including the Myawaddy Sayadaw and Shwe Nyar War Sayadaw, outspoken critics of the military.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] 8888 Uprising activist leaders, including Mya Aye, were also arrested.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] As of 4 February, the Assistance Association for Political Prisoners had identified 133 officials and lawmakers and 14 civil society activists in detention by the military as a result of the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Soldiers were seen in Naypyidaw and the largest city, Yangon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The military subsequently announced on military-controlled Myawaddy TV that it had taken control of the country for one year.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] A statement signed by Acting President Myint Swe declared that responsibility for "legislation, administration and judiciary" had been transferred to Min Aung Hlaing.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The military also announced the removal of 24 ministers and deputies, for whom 11 replacements were named.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 2 February 2021, Min Aung Hlaing established the State Administration Council, with 11 members, as the executive governing body.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 3 February 2021, Myanmar police filed criminal charges against Aung San Suu Kyi, accusing her of violating the Export and Import Law, for allegedly importing unlicensed communications devices used by her security detail, after conducting a raid on her home in the capital.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The Export and Import Law carries a potential prison term of 3 years and/or a fine, and was previously used in 2017 to prosecute journalists for flying a drone above the Assembly of the Union.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Meanwhile, Win Myint was charged with violating the Natural Disaster Management Law, specifically for waving at a passing NLD convoy in September 2020, thereby violating rules against election campaigning during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 6 February 2021, Sean Turnell, the Australian economic advisor to the civilian government, was arrested.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 8 February 2021 and 9 February 2021, the military government issued orders to impose curfew from 8:00 pm to 4:00 am in Yangon and other major cities and restrict gatherings of 5 or more people in the public spaces.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 9 February 2021, the NLD's headquarters in Yangon was raided by Myanmar police.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Myanmar's military regime distributed a draft for the controversial Cyber Security Law to internet service providers, asking them to provide comments by 15 February 2021.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The law was widely criticised by IT communities as it violates human rights by putting citizens under digital surveillance and severely restricting freedom of speech.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] News of China's involvement in building the firewall were widely circulated among Myanmar social media users, which prompts protestors to demonstrate outside the Chinese Embassy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 10 February 2021, civil servants at Kayah State protested against the coup, which also included police officers stationed there when they refused orders from their superior to return to work.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 12 February 2021, at midnight, members of Myanmar's military and police arrested government ministers, election officials, senior members of the NLD, activists, and a former general.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 13 February 2021, a viral post online showed that the military-run Ministry of Information (MOI) pressured the press not to use the words "junta" and "regime" in the media in the military's first attempt to restrict the freedom-of-press.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The military regime issued an arrest warrant for seven well-known activists and influencers including Min Ko Naing for "using their fame to spread writing and speaking on the social media that would disturb the nation's peace process".
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 15 February 2021, the military deployed armoured vehicles across the cities, in an attempt to silence the demonstrations in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Thousands of protestors in different cities across Myanmar had been calling for the release of Aung San Suu Kyi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 16 February, as protests continued, Aung San Suu Kyi was given a new criminal charge on allegations of violating the country's National Disaster Law.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 17 February 2021, the military issued arrest warrants on six more celebrities for urging civil servants to join the civil disobedience movement.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 26 February 2021, the Myanmar ambassador to the United Nations, Kyaw Moe Tun, condemned the coup by the Tatmadaw.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] He was sacked from his post the next day.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On the same day, a Japanese freelance journalist named Yuki Kitazumi was detained by Myanmar officers at the Sanchaung township police station, but he was released hours later after Kitazumi explained that he clearly identified himself as a reporter.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 8 March 2021, state-controlled channel MRTV announced that the Ministry of Information revoked the licences for five local media outlets: Mizzima, Myanmar Now, DVB, 7 Day News, and Khit Thit Media.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The announcement stated that the outlets were prohibited from publishing and broadcasting in any type of media and by using any sort of technology.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 9 March 2021, Kyaw Zwar Minn, the Burmese ambassador to the United Kingdom, was recalled after he called for release of Aung San Suu Kyi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 18 October 2021, Min Aung Hlaing announced the release of 5,636 prisoners jailed for protesting against the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] According to the Assistance Association for Political Prisoners, more than 7,300 protesters remained imprisoned across the country following the announcement.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 10 January 2022, Aung San Suu Kyi was convicted and sentenced to four years in prison for possessing walkie-talkies in her home and for violating COVID-19 protocols.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 1 August 2022, Myanmar junta's extended the state of emergency for another six months, after the leader Min Aung Hlaing's request to "serve for an additional 6 months".
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The decision was unanimously taken by the junta's National Defence and Security Council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Armed insurgencies by the People's Defence Force of the National Unity Government have erupted throughout Myanmar in response to the military government's crackdown on anti-coup protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 17 April 2026, President Win Myint was released after being granted amnesty during the Myanmar New Year’s Day.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The military's motives for the coup remain unclear.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Ostensibly, the military has posited that alleged voter fraud threatened national sovereignty.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] A few days before the coup, the civilian-appointed Union Election Commission had categorically rejected the military's claims of voter fraud, citing the lack of evidence to support the military's claims of 8.6 million irregularities in voter lists across Myanmar's 314 townships.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The coup may have been driven by the military's goal to preserve its central role in Burmese politics.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The Defence Services Act imposes a mandatory retirement age of 65 for the Armed Forces' Commander-in-Chief.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Min Aung Hlaing, the incumbent, would have been forced to retire on his 65th birthday in July 2021.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Hlaing's lack of power would have exposed him to potential prosecution and accountability for alleged war crimes during the Rohingya conflict in various international courts.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Min Aung Hlaing had also hinted a potential entry into politics as a civilian, after his retirement.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The activist group Justice for Myanmar has also noted the significant financial and business interests of Min Aung Hlaing and his family as a potential motivating factor for the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Min Aung Hlaing oversees two military conglomerates, the Myanmar Economic Corporation (MEC) and Myanma Economic Holdings Limited (MEHL), while his daughter, son, and daughter-in-law have substantial business holdings in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] A few days before the coup, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) had released US$372 million in cash loans to the Central Bank of Myanmar, as part of an emergency aid package, to help address the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The funds came with no conditions, and without any precedent for refunds.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] A lobbyist for the military junta reported that the junta would like to improve relations with the United States and distance Myanmar from China, believing Myanmar had grown too close to China under Aung San Suu Kyi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] China is depicted in Western media as having hegemony over Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] China and Russia vetoed a United Nations Security Council resolution condemning the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] China and Russia are reportedly the main suppliers of weapons to the Myanmar Army.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Chinese foreign direct investment in Myanmar totalled $19 billion in 2019, compared with $700 million from the EU.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The *Financial Times* argues that Russia is supportive of the junta in order to sell more arms to them.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The Myanmar military government did not attend the 27 October 2021 East Asia Summit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The United States and ASEAN (chaired by Brunei) criticized the junta's treatment of political prisoners, and Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen described Myanmar's decision to skip the summit as "regrettable".
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] US President Joe Biden said "We must address the tragedy caused by the military coup which is increasingly undermining regional stability," and called for the "military regime to end the violence, release all political prisoners and return to the path of democracy".
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] While ASEAN urged constitutional government, it also officially "reiterated that Myanmar remains a member of the ASEAN family".
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The legality of the coup has been questioned by legal scholars, including Melissa Crouch.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The International Commission of Jurists found that, by staging a coup, the military had violated Myanmar's constitution, since the alleged election irregularities did not justify the declaration of a state of emergency in comport with the Constitution.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Further, the jurists found that the military's actions had violated the fundamental rule of law principle.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The NLD has also rejected the legal basis for the military takeover.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] During its announcement of the coup, the military stated that, during a meeting chaired by Min Aung Hlaing, the NDSC had invoked Articles 417 and 418 of the 2008 Constitution and that this served as the legal basis for the military takeover.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The incumbent civilian president Win Myint had not voluntarily ceded his role; instead, the state of emergency was unconstitutionally declared by vice-president Myint Swe.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] During Win Myint's court testimony on 12 October, he revealed that on 1 February before the coup, two senior military generals had attempted to force him to resign, under the guise of "ill health".
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The declaration of a state of emergency then transfers legislative, executive, and judicial authority to the Commander-in-Chief per Article 418.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 23 March 2021, during a news conference in Naypyidaw, the Tatmadaw defended the reimposition of the junta and claimed that ousted national leader Aung San Suu Kyi was corrupt, tantamount to graft.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] No supporting evidence for these allegations was offered outside of the taped testimony of a former colleague of Kyi, Phyo Min Thein, who has been detained by the military since the coup began.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The three-finger salute has been widely adopted as a protest symbol, while netizens joined the Milk Tea Alliance, an online democratic solidarity movement in Asia.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] "Kabar Ma Kyay Bu" (ကမ္ဘာမကျေဘူး), a song that was first popularised as the anthem of the 8888 Uprising, has been revitalised by the civil disobedience movement as a protest song.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Since the onset of the coup, residents in urban centres such as Yangon staged cacerolazos, striking pots and pans in unison every evening as a symbolic act to drive away evil, as a method of expressing their opposition to the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 2 February, healthcare workers and civil servants across the country launched a national civil disobedience campaign, in opposition to the coup, with workers from dozens of state-run hospitals and institutions initiating a labour strike.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] A Facebook campaign group, dubbed the "Civil Disobedience Movement", has attracted 150,000 followers within 24 hours of its launch on 2 February.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] As of 3 February, healthcare workers in over 110 government hospitals and healthcare agencies have participated in the movement.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The labour strikes have spread to other parts of the civil service, including union-level ministries and universities, as well as to private firms, such as factories and copper mines, students, and youth groups.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 3 February, healthcare workers launched the red ribbon campaign (ဖဲကြိုးနီလှုပ်ရှားမှု), the colour red being associated with the NLD.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The red ribbon has been adopted by civil servants and workers across Myanmar as a symbol of opposition to the military regime.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 3 February, a domestic boycott movement called the "Stop Buying Junta Business" campaign also emerged, calling for the boycott of products and services linked to the Myanmar military.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Among the targeted goods and services in the Burmese military's significant business portfolio include Mytel, a national telecoms carrier, Myanmar, Mandalay, and Dagon Beer, several coffee and tea brands, 7th Sense Creation, which was co-founded by Min Aung Hlaing's daughter, and bus lines.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Public protests have also emerged in the wake of the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 2 February, some Yangonites staged a brief 15-minute protest rally at 8 pm, calling for the overthrow of the dictatorship and Aung San Suu Kyi's release.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 4 February, thirty people, led by Tayzar San, protested against the coup in front of the University of Medicine in Mandalay, leading to four arrests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 6 February, 20,000 protestors took part in a street protest in Yangon against the coup, calling for Aung San Suu Kyi to be released.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Workers from 14 trade unions participated in the protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Protests spread to Mandalay and to the Pyinmana township of Naypyidaw on the afternoon of 6 February.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Protestors continued on motorbikes at 4:00 pm in reaction to police restrictions.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 9 February 2021, the military used violence to crackdown on peaceful protests, injuring six protestors, including a 20-year-old woman who was shot in the head.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] About 100 demonstrators were arrested in Mandalay.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 10 February 2021, most of the arrested demonstrators from Mandalay were released.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 12 February, the Union Day in Myanmar, junta's crackdown in Mawlamyine became more intense as shots were fired.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Gunfire was heard in Myitkyina, Kachin State, when security forces clashed with protesters on 14 February.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Five journalists were arrested afterwards.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Troops joined police in forcefully dispersing marchers using rubber bullets and slingshots in the city of Mandalay.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Facebook had been used to organise the civil disobedience campaign's labour strikes and the emerging boycott movement.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 4 February, telecom operators and internet providers across Myanmar were ordered to block Facebook until 7 February, to ensure the "country's stability".
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] MPT, a state-owned carrier, also blocked Facebook Messenger, Instagram and WhatsApp services, while Telenor Myanmar blocked only Facebook.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Following the Facebook ban, Burmese users had begun flocking to Twitter, popularising hashtags like #RespectOurVotes, #HearTheVoiceofMyanmar, and #SaveMyanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 5 February, the government extended the social media access ban to include Instagram and Twitter.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On the morning of 6 February, the military authorities initiated an internet outage nationwide.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Internet access was restricted by the government again since 14 February 2021 for 20 days, from 1:00 am to 9:00 am.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] People have used social media like Facebook and Twitter to reach their voices to international communities and also to share photo and video evidence of brutality of military forces on the protestors.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Various Buddhist monasteries and educational institutions have denounced the coup, among them the Masoyein and Mahāgandhārāma monasteries.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Sitagu International Buddhist Academy also released a statement imploring against actions that run counter to the *Dhamma*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Aside from the Buddhist *saṅgha*, local clergy and monastics of the Catholic Church have similarly voiced their opposition to the military takeover.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] As the military response to the ensuing protests started taking a violent turn, the Shwekyin Nikāya, Burma's second largest monastic order, urged Min Aung Hlaing to immediately cease the assaults on unarmed civilians and to refrain from engaging in theft and property destruction.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Its leading monks, including Ñāṇissara Bhikkhu, who is known for his amicable relationship with the military, reminded the general to be a good Buddhist, which entailed keeping to the Five Precepts required for rebirth as at least a human.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Thailand's largest industrial estate developer, Amata, halted a $1 billion industrial zone development project in Yangon in response to the coup, having started construction in December 2020.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Suzuki Motor, Myanmar's largest automaker, and several manufacturers halted domestic operations in the wake of the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The Yangon Stock Exchange has also suspended trading since 1 February.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Myanmar's real estate market crashed as a result of the coup, with sales and purchase transactions dropping by almost 100%.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 4 February, French oil multinational Total SE announced it was reviewing the impact of the coup on its domestic operations and projects.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 4 April, it issued a statement saying it would not withhold payments to the military junta and would not cease operations in its Yadana offshore gasfield where electricity is generated for public use.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] A couple of weeks later there were reports of US oil giant Chevron lobbying against United States Department of State sanctions restricting the company in its capacity as "a non-operating partner" in the Yadana field through an affiliate.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 5 February, Kirin Company ended its joint venture with the military-owned Myanma Economic Holdings Limited (MEHL).
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The joint venture, Myanmar Brewery, produces several brands of beer, including Myanmar Beer, and has an 80% market share in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Kirin's stake had been valued at US$1.7 billion.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 8 February, Lim Kaling, early investor of Razer announced he was divesting his stake in a joint venture with a Singaporean tobacco company that owns a 49% stake in Virginia Tobacco, whose majority stake is owned by MEHL.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Virginia Tobacco, Myanmar's largest cigarette maker, owns the Red Ruby and Premium Gold brands.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] That evening, Min Aung Hlaing made a televised address, aiming to ease concerns about Myanmar's foreign investment climate.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] US President Joe Biden and his administration imposed sanctions on the military leaders of the coup in Myanmar and froze 1 billion dollars in government assets held in the United States on 11 February 2021.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] After several protesters were shot dead by the military during the protests on February, Facebook responded by suspending several accounts belonging to the government including Tatmadaw and its news website, Tatmadaw True News, and MRTV, due to these pages linked to promoting violence.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 25 February, Facebook banned all accounts of the Tatmadaw, along with its related commercial entities.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Parent company Facebook Inc (now Meta) also implemented the ban on Instagram.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Other tech companies follow suit, with YouTube terminated several channels belonging to governments including MRTV and Myawaddy TV, and TikTok restricting several violence contents from being available in their platform.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 16 April 2021, South Korean steel giant Posco announced that its Myanmar subsidiary, POSCO C&C, would end its relationship with military-owned Myanma Economic Holdings Limited (MEHL).
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 27 October, Indian-owned Adani Ports & SEZ announced it would terminate its US$127 million investment in Myanmar to construct a container terminal in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Foreign direct investment in Myanmar fell to an eight-year low, dropping 22% to US$3.8 billion in Myanmar's 2020 fiscal year (September 2020 and September 2021), due to the combined pressures of COVID and political unrest following the February coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] As the protests have started, there have been reported defections from the Myanmar Police Force.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 5 March 2021, 11 officers were seen to have crossed the India–Myanmar land border to Mizoram state with their families due to refusing orders to engage protestors by using lethal force.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Myanmar officials have reached out to India to repatriate the defecting police officers located in Mizoram, with the reply that the Indian government will make a final decision.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The Assam Rifles were given orders to tighten security along the India–Myanmar border.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] As of 5 March 2021, more than 600 police officers have joined the anti-regime movement, some of whom have served as police officers for many years and have collected awards for their outstanding performances.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] From 10 March, the border has been closed after 48 Burmese nationals have crossed it.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Some military personnel from Tatmadaw also left their posts to stand with the people against the military junta.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Among them are Captain Tun Myat Aung from the 77th Light Infantry Division and Major Hein Thaw Oo from the 99th Light Infantry Division who holds the highest rank among the known defectors from Myanmar's military as of 21 April 2021.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Both of them cited the corruption among the high-ranked military officers and the lack of will to kill their own people as main reasons for their defection.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Many countries, including Bangladesh, China, India, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Pakistan, the Philippines, South Korea, and Singapore, encouraged dialogue between the government and the military in order to resolve the issue, many of which expressed concern in response to the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Australia, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Nepal, New Zealand, South Korea, Spain, Sweden, Turkey, the United Kingdom, and the United States condemned the coup and called for the release of detained officials; the White House also threatened to impose sanctions on coup perpetrators.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Cambodia, Thailand, and Vietnam explicitly refused to support either side, characterising the coup as an internal matter.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 9 February 2021, New Zealand suspended diplomatic contact with Myanmar and prohibited government military leaders from entering New Zealand because of the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 25 February 2021, Tokyo considered halting projects in Myanmar in response to the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 24 February, the new Myanmar foreign minister visited Thailand, marking the first high official visit since the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Malaysian Prime Minister Muhyiddin Yassin and Indonesian President Joko Widodo called a special meeting of ASEAN foreign ministers to discuss the issue during Muhyiddin's visit to Jakarta.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In March, reports appeared in the Thai press accusing the Thai military of supplying rice to the Myanmar military, which it denied.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 26 February 2021, the South Korean National Assembly passed a resolution condemning the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 5 March 2021, Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Katsunobu Kato urged the SAC-led government to stop using lethal force to disperse protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Singaporean foreign minister Vivian Balakrishnan also called the military to stop using lethal force.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 27 March 2021, eight countries ‑ India, China, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Vietnam, Laos, Thailand and Russia ‑ sent representatives to attend the Myanmar Armed Forces Day parade.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Intergovernmental organisations, including the United Nations, ASEAN, and the European Union expressed concern and called for dialogue from both sides.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In addition to concern, the European Union also condemned the coup and urged the release of detainees.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In response to the coup, the United Nations Security Council held an emergency meeting, where a British-drafted resolution urging the "restoration of democracy" in Myanmar, condemning the Myanmar military's action, and calling for the release of detainees was proposed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The first draft of the statement was not issued because of failure to garner support from all 15 council members; the diplomats of China and Russia reportedly had to relay the draft to their respective governments for review.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] China and Russia, as permanent members of the council and therefore having the power of veto, refused to back the statement.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] India and Vietnam, two non-permanent members, also "voiced reservations" about the resolution.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The UNSC presidential statement further urged all parties to cooperate with mediation efforts of the ASEAN, and the U.N. envoy to Myanmar, and to ensure access to humanitarian aid for all in Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] ASEAN called for a special ASEAN Leaders Meeting in Jakarta on 24 April 2021, with Min Aung Hlaing in attendance along with other member states' heads of government and foreign ministers.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Members of the National Unity Government formed in response to the coup and consisting of ousted lawmakers were reported to have been in contact with ASEAN leaders, but were not formally invited to the meeting.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] During the summit, Min Aung Hlaing was not referred to as a head of state.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] ASEAN released a statement that it had agreed to a "five-point consensus" with Min Aung Hlaing on the cessation of violence in Myanmar, constructive dialogue among all parties concerned, and the appointment of a special envoy by ASEAN to facilitate the dialogue process.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 28 May 2021, the governments of Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam proposed that a U.N. draft resolution on Myanmar be watered down, including removing a call for an arms embargo against the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Special Rapporteur Tom Andrews urged the U.N.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Security Council and member states to advance a "COVID ceasefire" in Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] At the time of his report, over 600 healthcare professionals were eluding outstanding arrest warrants and 67 had already been detained in the midst of soaring COVID-19 infections and deaths throughout the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] A group of about 200 Burmese expatriates and some Thai pro-democracy activists protested the coup at the Burmese embassy on Sathon Nuea Road in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Some protesters reportedly showed the three-finger salute, the symbol used in the protests calling for democracy in Thailand.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The protest ended with a police crackdown; two protestors were injured and hospitalised, and two others were arrested.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] Burmese citizens in Tokyo, Japan gathered in front of the United Nations University, also to protest against the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 3 February, more than 150 Burmese Americans protested in front of the Embassy of Myanmar in Washington, D.C.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The Singapore Police Force issued warnings on 5 February 2021 against foreigners planning to participate in anti-coup protests in Singapore.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 14 February 2021, SPF officers arrested three foreigners for protesting at the outskirts of the Myanmar embassy without permits to participate in a public assembly.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] In March 2021, the Public Security Police Force of Macau has warned Myanmar residents that they are not allowed to conduct anti-coup protests as Article 27 of the Macau Basic Law only allows Macanese residents the right to do so.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 4 February 2021, Japanese expats living/working in Myanmar were evacuated from Yangon International Airport to Narita International Airport after the coup on 1 February.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 21 February, Taiwanese government started the evacuation process of Taiwanese expatriates in Myanmar, Taiwanese government also urged Taiwanese expatriates who wished to go back to get in touch with China Airlines.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On 7 March, the South Korean government ordered a chartered Korean Air flight from Yangon to Seoul to return South Korean expatriates from Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] On the same day, the Indonesian and Singaporean governments urged their citizens to leave Myanmar as soon as possible due to safety reasons.
[src:burmese-cuisine/2021-myanmar-coup-d-état] The British government also urged British citizens who stayed in Myanmar to immediately leave the country due to rising violence.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The **8888 Uprising**, also known as the **1988 Uprising**, was a series of nationwide protests, marches, and riots in Burma (present-day Myanmar) that peaked in August 1988.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Key events occurred on 8 August 1988 and therefore it is commonly known as the "8888 Uprising".
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The protests began as a student movement and were organised largely by university students at the Rangoon Arts and Sciences University and the Rangoon Institute of Technology.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Since the 1962 military coup, the Burma Socialist Programme Party had ruled the country as a totalitarian one-party state, headed by General Ne Win.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Under the government agenda, called the Burmese Way to Socialism, which involved economic isolation and the strengthening of the military, Burma became one of the world's most impoverished countries.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Many firms in the formal sector of the economy were nationalised, and the government combined Soviet-style central planning with Buddhist and traditional beliefs and superstition.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The 8888 uprising was started by students in Yangon (Rangoon) on 8 August 1988.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Student protests spread throughout the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Hundreds of thousands of monks, children, university students, housewives, doctors and common people protested against the government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The uprising ended on 18 September after a bloody military coup by the State Law and Order Restoration Council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Thousands of deaths have been attributed to the military during this uprising, while authorities in Burma put the figure at around 350 people killed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] During the crisis, Aung San Suu Kyi emerged as a national icon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] When the military junta arranged an election in 1990, her party, the National League for Democracy, won 81% of the seats in the government (392 out of 492).
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] However, the military junta refused to recognise the results and continued to rule the country as the State Law and Order Restoration Council.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Aung San Suu Kyi was also placed under house arrest.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The State Law and Order Restoration Council would be a cosmetic change from the Burma Socialist Programme Party.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Suu Kyi's house arrest was lifted in 2010, when worldwide attention for her peaked again during the making of the biographical film *The Lady*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The Tatmadaw (Myanmar Armed Forces) again seized control of the country in the 2021 Myanmar coup d'état, which began with the imprisonment of then State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The coup has led to numerous protests and demonstrations against the military-led government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Activists have compared the current coup resistance movement to the 8888 Uprising.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Before the crisis, Burma had been ruled by the repressive and isolated regime of General Ne Win since 1962.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The country had a national debt of $3.5 billion and currency reserves of between $20 million and $35 million, with debt service ratios standing at half of the national budget.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] One reason for the deficit came from the government's spending on the military against Communist and ethnic insurgents.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] This spending amounted to 40% of the national budget, while these insurgents denied the government access to mineral-rich parts of the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In the years leading up to the crisis, General Ne Win had imposed two instances of sudden currency demonetisation that declared certain circulated denominations of currency invalid.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] These instances led to instantaneous loss of savings for many Burmese citizens and economic instability.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 3 November 1985, the Burmese government declared notes of 20, 50, and 100 kyats invalid, without prior warning to the public.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Prior to this, circulated denominations were of 1, 5, 10, 20, 50, and 100 kyats.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The stated reason for the demonetisation was to combat black market activity.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The public was given only a short period of time to exchange their 20, 50, and 100 kyat bills, and only 25% of the value of surrendered bills were reimbursed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 10 November 1985, a week after the initial announcement of demonetisation, new denominations of 25, 35, and 75 kyat bills were announced, with the 75 kyat denomination chosen to commemorate Ne Win's 75th birthday.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In November 1985, students gathered and boycotted the government's decision to withdraw Burmese local currency notes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Economic problems coupled with counter-insurgency required continuous involvement in the international market.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 5 September 1987, Ne Win announced the demonetisation of the 25, 35, and 75 kyat notes, leaving only the 1, 5, and 10 kyat bills valid.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] This announcement was also with no prior warning, and this time no exchange for valid tender was allowed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Roughly 60–80% of circulated legal tender was declared invalid without warning, and millions of Burmese citizens had their savings eliminated by this action.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 22 September 1987, the Burmese government introduced new denominations of 45 and 90 kyat notes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The 45 and 90 kyat denominations were chosen because the two numbers are divisible by 9, which was considered lucky by Ne Win.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Students in particular were angry at the 1987 demonetisation as savings for tuition fees were wiped out instantly.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Students from the Rangoon Institute of Technology (RIT) rioted throughout Rangoon, smashing windows and traffic lights down Insein Road, and universities in Rangoon temporarily closed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The government later allowed for reimbursement of up to 100 kyat so that students could return home instead of rioting in the cities.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] With the re-opening of schools in late October 1987, underground groups in Rangoon and Mandalay produced dissident leaflets which culminated in bombs exploding in November.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Police later received threatening letters from underground groups, who organised small protests around the university campus.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Meanwhile, larger protests in Mandalay involved monks and workers, with some burning government buildings and state businesses.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Burmese state media reported little on the protests, but information quickly spread through the students.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] After receiving Least Developed Country status from the United Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) in December 1987, government policy requiring farmers to sell produce below market rates to create greater revenue for the government sparked several, violent rural protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The protests were fanned by public letters to Ne Win by former second in command Brigadier General Aung Gyi from July 1987, reminding him of the 1967 riots and condemning lack of economic reform, describing Burma as "almost a joke" compared to other Southeast Asian nations.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 12 March 1988, students from the Rangoon Institute of Technology (RIT) were arguing with out-of-school youths inside the *Sanda Win* tea shop about music playing on a sound system.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] A drunken youth would not return a tape that the RIT students favoured.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] A brawl followed in which one youth, who was the son of a Burma Socialist Programme Party (BSPP) official, was arrested and later released for injuring a student.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Students protested at a local police department where 500 riot police were mobilised and in the ensuing clash, one student, Phone Maw, was shot and killed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The incident angered pro-democracy groups and the next day more students rallied at the RIT and spread to other campuses.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The students, who had never protested before, increasingly saw themselves as activists.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] There was growing resentment towards military rule and there were no channels to address grievances, further exacerbated by police brutality, economic mismanagement, and corruption within the government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] By mid-March, several protests had occurred and there was open dissent in the army.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Various demonstrations were broken up by using tear gas canisters to disperse crowds.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 16 March, students demanding an end to one party rule marched towards soldiers at Inya Lake when riot police stormed from the rear, clubbing several students to death and raping others.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Several students recalled the police shouting, "Don't let them escape" and "Kill them!".
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 28 March, the Communist Party of Burma issued a statement in support of the protests, calling for the creation of a provisional government that would unite the revolutionaries and protestors of Burma.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Following the latest protests, authorities announced the closure of universities for several months.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] By June 1988, large demonstrations of students and sympathisers were a daily sight.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Many students, sympathisers and riot police died throughout the month as the protests spread throughout Burma from Rangoon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Largescale protests were reported in Pegu, Mandalay, Tavoy, Toungoo, Sittwe, Pakokku, Mergui, Minbu and Myitkyina.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Demonstrators in larger numbers demanded multi-party democracy, which marked Ne Win's resignation on 23 July 1988.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In a valedictory address given that day, Ne Win affirmed that "When the army shoots, it shoots to kill." He also promised a multi-party system, but he appointed the largely disliked Sein Lwin, known as the "Butcher of Rangoon" to head a new government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Protests reached their peak in August 1988.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Students planned for a nationwide demonstration on 8 August 1988, an auspicious date based on numerological significance.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] News of the protest reached rural areas and four days prior to the national protest, students across the country were denouncing Sein Lwin's regime and Tatmadaw troops were being mobilised.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Pamphlets and posters appeared on the streets of Rangoon bearing the fighting peacock insignia of the All-Burma Students Union.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Neighbourhood and strike committees were openly formed on the advice of underground activists, many of which were influenced by similar underground movements by workers and monks in the 1980s.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Between 2 and 10 August, co-ordinated protests were occurring in most Burmese towns.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In the first few days of the Rangoon protests, activists contacted lawyers and monks in Mandalay to encourage them to take part in the protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The students were quickly joined by Burmese citizens from all walks of life, including government workers, Buddhist monks, air force and navy personnel, customs officers, teachers and hospital staff.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The demonstrations in the streets of Rangoon became a focal point for other demonstrations, which spread to other states' capitals.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Upwards of 10,000 protesters demonstrated outside the Sule Pagoda in Rangoon, where demonstrators burned and buried effigies of Ne Win and Sein Lwin in coffins decorated with demonetised bank notes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Further protests took place around the country at stadiums and hospitals.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Monks at the Sule Pagoda reported that the Buddha's image had changed shape, with an image in the sky standing on its head.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 3 August, the authorities imposed martial law from 8 pm to 4 am and a ban on gatherings of more than five people.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] A general strike, as planned, began on 8 August 1988.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Mass demonstrations were held across Burma as ethnic minorities, Buddhists, Christians, Muslims, students, workers and the young and old all demonstrated.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The first procession circled Rangoon, stopping for people to speak.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Demonstrators from the Rangoon neighbourhoods converged in downtown Rangoon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Only one casualty was reported at this point as a frightened traffic policeman fired into the crowd and fled.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Lwin had brought in more soldiers from insurgent areas to deal with the protesters.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In Mandalay Division, a more organised strike committee was headed by lawyers and discussion focused on multi-party democracy and human rights.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Many participants in the protests arrived from nearby towns and villages.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Farmers who were particularly angry with the government's economic policies joined the protests in Rangoon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In one village, 2,000 of the 5,000 people also went on strike.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] A short while later, the authorities opened fire on the protesters.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Ne Win ordered that "guns were not to shoot upwards", meaning that he was ordering the military to shoot directly at the demonstrators.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Protesters responded by throwing Molotov cocktails, swords, knives, rocks, poisoned darts and bicycle spokes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In one incident, protesters burned a police station and tore apart four fleeing officers.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 10 August, soldiers fired into Rangoon General Hospital, killing nurses and doctors tending to the wounded.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] State-run Radio Rangoon reported that 1,451 "looters and disturbance makers" had been arrested.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] While estimates of the number of casualties surrounding the 8-8-88 demonstrations range from hundreds to 10,000; military authorities put the figures at about 95 people killed and 240 wounded.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Lwin's sudden and unexplained resignation on 12 August left many protestors confused and jubilant.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Security forces exercised greater caution with demonstrators, particularly in neighbourhoods that were entirely controlled by demonstrators and committees.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 19 August, under pressure to form a civilian government, Ne Win's biographer, Maung Maung, was appointed as head of government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Maung was a legal scholar and the only non-military individual to serve in the Burma Socialist Programme Party (BSPP).
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The appointment of Maung briefly resulted in a subsidence of the shooting and protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Nationwide demonstrations resumed on 22 August 1988.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In Mandalay, 100,000 people protested, including Buddhist monks and 50,000 demonstrated in Sittwe.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Large marches took places from Taunggyi and Moulmein to distant ethnic states (particularly where military campaigns had previously taken place), where red, the symbolic colour for democracy was displayed on banners.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Two days later, doctors, monks, musicians, actors, lawyers, army veterans and government office workers joined the protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] It became difficult for committees to control the protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] During this time, demonstrators became increasingly wary of "suspicious looking" people and police and army officers.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On one occasion, a local committee mistakenly beheaded a couple thought to have been carrying a bomb.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Incidents like these were not as common in Mandalay, where protests were more peaceful as they were organised by monks and lawyers.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 26 August, Aung San Suu Kyi, who had watched the demonstrations from her mother's bedside, entered the political arena by addressing half a million people at Shwedagon Pagoda.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] It was at this point that she became a symbol for the struggle in Burma, particularly in the eyes of the Western world.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Suu Kyi, as the daughter of Aung San, who led the independence movement, appeared ready to lead the movement for democracy..
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 28 August, the Communist Party of Burma became the first of active insurgent forces in the country to comment on the revolution, where it identified itself with the goal of the 8888 Uprising and congratulated the students and people for their victories.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Though the Communist Party did not lead the uprising, some demonstrations in Rangoon and Mandalay had come under the influence of the communists, primarily a CPB cell named '4828 Regional Committee' and various communist guerrillas who had surrendered before the uprising.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Around this time, former Prime Minister U Nu and retired Brigadier General Aung Gyi also re-emerged onto the political scene in what was described as a "democracy summer" when many former democracy leaders returned.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Despite the gains made by the democracy movement, Ne Win remained in the background.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] A rival government was formed by U Nu on 9 September with him as prime minister.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] However, this move was not co-ordinated with other parts of the uprising, and thus resulted in condemnations and a widening split in the opposition who viewed U Nu's move as opportunism.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] During the September congress of 1988, 90% of party delegates (968 out of 1080) voted for a multi-party system of government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The Burma Socialist Programme Party (BSPP) announced they would be organising an election, but the opposition parties called for their immediate resignation from government, allowing an interim government to organise elections.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] After the BSPP rejected both demands, protesters again took to the streets on 12 September 1988.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Nu promised elections within a month, proclaiming a provisional government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Meanwhile, the police and army began fraternising with the protesters.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The movement had reached an impasse relying on three hopes: daily demonstrations to force the regime to respond to their demands, encouraging soldiers to defect and appealing to an international audience in the hope that United Nations or United States troops would arrive.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Some Tatmadaw did defect, but only in limited numbers, mostly from the Navy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Stephen Solarz who had experienced the recent democracy protests in the Philippines and South Korea arrived in Burma in September encouraging the regime to reform, which echoed the policy of the United States government towards Burma.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] By mid-September, the protests grew more violent and lawless, with soldiers deliberately leading protesters into skirmishes that the army easily won.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Protesters demanded more immediate change, and distrusted steps for incremental reform.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 17 September, dozens of activists and monks occupied the Ministry of Trade building and seized the weapons of its security personnel.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On the same day, the Communist Party of Burma issued a call for a ceasefire, overthrow of the BSPP, multi-party elections, and talks with opposition parties, which was welcomed by veteran communists and the left-wing leaders of the uprising.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The army had by this point already been planning a repression of the uprising, but was incensed to do so as young military personnel began to take part in the uprising, some of whom had established contacts at the Rangoon Worker's College, where a very militant Student Union had taken control.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Furthermore, students and rank-and-file members of the opposition were angered by the failure of the oppositon's leadership to form an interim government.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Thus, radical activists within the All Burma Student's Federation called for a meeting on 18 September to create a parallel government composed of strike-committees and worker's unions.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 18 September 1988, the military retook power in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] General Saw Maung repealed the 1974 constitution and established the State Law and Order Restoration Council (SLORC), "imposing more draconian measures than Ne Win had imposed." After Maung had imposed martial law, the protests were violently broken up.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The government announced on the state-run radio that the military had assumed power in the people's interest, "in order to bring a timely halt to the deteriorating conditions on all sides all over the country".
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Tatmadaw troops went through cities throughout Burma, indiscriminately firing on protestors.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Protestors were also pursued into the jungle and some students took up training on the country's borders with Thailand.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] By the end of September, there were around 3,000 estimated deaths and unknown number of injured, with 1,000 deaths in Rangoon alone.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] At this point in time, Aung San Suu Kyi appealed for help.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On 21 September, the government had regained control of the country, with the movement effectively collapsing in October.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] By the end of 1988, it was estimated that 10,000 people, including protesters and soldiers, had been killed.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Many in Burma believed that the regime would have collapsed if the United Nations and neighbouring countries had refused to recognise the legitimacy of the coup.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Western governments and Japan cut aid to the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Among Burma's neighbours, India was most critical; condemning the suppression, closing borders and setting up refugee camps along its border with Burma.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] By 1989, 6,000 NLD supporters had been detained and those who fled to the ethnic border areas, such as Kawthoolei, formed groups with those who sought greater self-determination.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] It was estimated 10,000 had fled to mountains which were controlled by ethnic insurgents such as the Karen National Liberation Army (KNLA), and many of them later trained to become soldiers.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Of these 10,000, most fled to land held by the NDF, though some also joined CPB territory in the Shan area.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] These revolutionaries who fled to the countryside to fight led to the intensification of insurgency.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] These offensives followed common bouts of fighting that emerged in the countries rainy season.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] After the uprising, the SLORC waged a "clumsy propaganda" campaign against those who had organised the protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Intelligence Chief General Khin Nyunt, held English-language press conferences which were aimed at giving foreign diplomats and the media a favourable account of the SLORC's response to the protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] During this period, more restrictions were imposed upon the Burmese media, denying it the relative freedom to report news which it had been able to exercise at the peak of the protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In the conferences, he detailed a conspiracy in which the right was plotting to overthrow the regime with the assistance of "subversive foreigners" and a conspiracy in which the left was plotting to overthrow the State.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Despite the conferences, few believed the government's version of events.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] While these conferences were going on, the SLORC was secretly negotiating with mutineers.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Between 1988 and 2000, the Burmese government established 20 museums which detailed the military's central role throughout Burma's history and the size of the military increased from 180,000 to 400,000.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The Burmese government also kept schools and universities closed in order to prevent future uprisings.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Initially, Aung San Suu Kyi, U Tin Oo and Aung Gyi publicly rejected the SLORC's offer to hold elections the following year, claiming that they could not be freely held while Burma was under military rule.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Today, the uprising is commemorated by Burmese expatriates and citizens.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] In Thailand, students also commemorate the uprising every 8 August.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] On the 20th anniversary of the uprising, 48 activists were arrested for commemorating the event in Burma.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The event garnered much support for the Burmese people internationally.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Poems were written by students who participated in the protests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The 1995 film *Beyond Rangoon* is a fictionalized drama which is based on the events that took place during the uprising.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The uprising led to the death and imprisonment of thousands of individuals.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Many of the deaths occurred inside the prisons, where prisoners of conscience were subjected to inhumane torture and deprived of basic provisions, such as food, water, medicine, and sanitation.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] From 1988 to 2012, the military and the police illegally detained and imprisoned tens of thousands of leaders of the Burmese pro-democracy movement, as well as intellectuals, artists, students, and human rights activists.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Pyone Cho, one of the leaders of the uprising, spent 20 years of his adult life in prison.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Ko Ko Gyi, another leader of the uprising, spent 18 years of his life in prison.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Min Ko Naing was placed in solitary confinement for nine years for his role as a leader of the uprising.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Because the uprising began as a student movement, many of the individuals who were arrested, imprisoned, tortured, and killed by the police and the military were high school and university students.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Many of the student leaders of the uprising became lifelong human rights activists and leaders of the Burmese pro-democracy movement.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Nineteen years later, many of these same activists also played a role in the 2007 Saffron Revolution.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The 88 Generation Students Group, which is named after the events of 8 August 1988, organised one of the first protests which eventually culminated in the Saffron Revolution.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] But prior to the outbreak of large-scale demonstrations, its members were arrested and given lengthy prison sentences of up to 65 years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] The activists who were arrested included prominent individuals such as Min Ko Naing, Mya Aye, Htay Kywe, Mie Mie, Ko Ko Gyi, Pyone Cho, Min Zeyar, Ant Bwe Kyaw, and Nilar Thein.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Though not an 88 Generation Students Group member, a solo protester Ohn Than also joined the demonstration.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] All of them were released in a general amnesty in 2012.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] They continue to work as politicians and human rights activists in Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] They also campaigned for the National League for Democracy (NLD) in the 2015 general election.
[src:burmese-cuisine/8888-uprising] Pyone Cho, one of the main leaders of the 88 Generation, was elected to the House of Representatives in the 2015 Election.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Georgia was one of the countries on the Silk Road, which resulted in travelers influencing Georgian cuisine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] The Georgian love of family and friends is one of the reasons why the *supra* (feast) is so important in Georgia.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] *Supra* is offered spontaneously to relatives, friends or guests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Every *supra* has its *tamada* (toastmaster), who gives the toast and entertains the guests.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Abkhazian cuisine uses many spices and walnuts.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] The most popular dessert is *akuarkuar*, a cookie with honey.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] *Ajika* is a hot, spicy, but subtly flavored sauce or paste, often used to flavor food.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] *Ajika* is also sold as a dry spice blend.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Abkhazian wines include Lykhny, Apsny, and Anakopia.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Adjarian cuisine is considered a very diversified cuisine, which has been influenced by its geography (seaside, mountainous part) and by its history.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] In the mountainous Adjara, the main products are dairy products and the dishes are more fat and heavy and on the other side, in the seaside of the region, dishes are mostly spiced, and use many fresh herbs.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] The cuisine of Guria is based mostly on poultry (especially chicken), cornbread (mchadi) and walnuts, like the cuisine of Imereti.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] The cuisine of Imereti shares many affinities with the neighbouring region of Guria and is known for its generous use of walnuts.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Imereti is known for its cheeses such as chkinti (ჭყინტი, salty cheese), Imeruli kveli (იმერული ყველი), and sulguni (სულგუნი).
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Kakhetian cuisine is considered to be a more meat-based cuisine and the region itself is called the "Region of Wine".
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] It is also known as the birthplace of one type of Georgian bread: Shoti.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Kartli is known as a very rich region in terms of fruits (especially apples, apricots, figs, and peaches) and vegetables (especially cucumbers, tomatoes, and onions).
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] The regional cuisine of Samegrelo can be considered the most famous in Georgia.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] These cuisines are often considered as one due to their similarities.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] The cuisines of Racha and of Lechkhumi share most of their dishes and are often grouped into one cuisine as a consequence.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] The Cuisine of Samtskhe-Javakheti consists of two regional cuisines: Meskhetian and Javakhetian.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Due to their similarities, they are often considered one regional cuisine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] This cuisine differs significantly from other regional cuisine of Georgia, partly because of its heavy use of goose meat and historical Turkish rule of the region.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Traditional Georgian breads are varied, and include Tonis Puri, Shotis Puri, Mesxuri Puri, Nazuki and Mchadi.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Georgian breads are traditionally baked in a large, round, well-shaped oven called a *tone*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Khachapuri, also spelled as hachapuri, is a traditional Georgian dish of cheese (fresh or aged, most commonly sulguni), eggs and other ingredients.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Georgia is the oldest wine-producing region in the world.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] The fertile valleys and protective slopes of the Transcaucasia were home to grapevine cultivation and neolithic wine production (Georgian: ღვინო, *ɣvino*) for at least 8000 years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Due to the many millennia of wine in Georgian history and its prominent economic role, the traditions of wine are considered entwined with and inseparable from the national identity.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Among the best-known Georgian wine regions are Kakheti (further divided into the micro-regions of Telavi and Kvareli), Kartli, Imereti, Racha-Lechkhumi and Kvemo Svaneti, Adjara and Abkhazia.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] UNESCO added the ancient traditional Georgian winemaking method using the Kvevri clay jars to the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Alcoholic drinks from Georgia include chacha and wine (especially Georgian wine).
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Some of the most well-known Georgian wines include Pirosmani, Alazani, Akhasheni, Saperavi, and Kindzmarauli.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Wine culture in Georgia dates back thousands of years, and many Georgian wines are made from traditional Georgian grape varieties that are little known in the West, such as Saperavi and Rkatsiteli.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Georgian wine is well known throughout Eastern Europe, and is a significant national export, with exports of over 10 million bottles of wine per year.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Georgia is also home to many beer brands, including Natakhtari, Kazbegi, Argo, Kasri, and Karva.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] There are also many craft beer brands such as Shavi Lomi, Megobrebi, NaturAle & Underground.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Lagidze water is a Georgian flavored soda drink, made with a variety of natural syrups, sold bottled or mixed directly in a glass from a soda fountain.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Common types of mineral water from Georgia include Borjomi, Nabeghlavi, Likani, and Sairme.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] Georgian cuisine is primarily popular in the post-Soviet states, although it also has been gaining popularity in the Western world in recent years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] As such, American magazine *Thrillist* placed Georgian cuisine as the 4th among the indigenous cuisines of the 48 European countries.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abkhaz-cuisine] In 2010, Georgian cuisine was described as having had an exotic appeal to Russians that *The Independent* compared to that of Indian cuisine to the British.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Pasta, meat, and vegetables are central to the cuisine of Abruzzo.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Chili peppers (Italian: *peperoncini*) are typical of Abruzzo, where they are called *diavoletti* (lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Due to the long history of shepherding in Abruzzo, lamb dishes are common.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Mushrooms (usually wild mushrooms), rosemary, and garlic are also extensively used in Abruzzese cuisine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Best-known is the extra virgin olive oil produced in the local farms on the hills of the region, marked by the quality level DOP and considered one of the best in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Renowned wines such as Montepulciano DOCG and Trebbiano d'Abruzzo DOC are considered amongst the world's finest wines.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] In 2012, a bottle of Trebbiano d'Abruzzo Colline Teramane ranked No.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] *Centerbe* is a strong (72% alcohol), spicy herbal liqueur drunk by the locals.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Another liqueur is *genziana*, a soft distillate of gentian roots.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] The best-known dish from Abruzzo is *arrosticini*, little pieces of castrated lamb on a wooden stick and cooked on coals.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] 'guitar') is a variety of egg pasta, with a square cross section about 2–3 mm thick.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] In the province of Teramo, famous local dishes include the *virtù* soup (made with legumes, vegetables, and pork meat), the *timballo* (pasta sheets filled with meat, vegetables or rice), and the *mazzarelle* (lamb intestines filled with garlic, marjoram, lettuce, and various spices).
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] The popularity of saffron, grown in the province of L'Aquila, has waned in recent years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Seafood also plays an important role in the cuisine of Abruzzo, especially areas near the coast.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Spreadable sausage flavored with nutmeg and liver sausage with garlic and spices are hallmarks of Teramo cuisine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] *Ventricina* from the Vasto area is made with large pieces of fat and lean pork, pressed and seasoned with powdered sweet peppers and fennel and encased in dried pig stomach.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Atri and Rivisondoli are known for their cheeses.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Mozzarella (fresh or seasoned) is typically made from ewe's milk; many lesser-known cheeses are found throughout Abruzzo and Molise.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] The use of oil in regional mountain and sea dishes is important; among the most common oil products we find the Aprutino Pescarese, the Pretuziano delle Colline Teramane, l'Olio extra vergine di oliva delle Valli Aquilane and Colline Teatine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Renowned wines like Montepulciano DOCG, Terre Tollesi DOCG, Trebbiano d'Abruzzo DOC and Controguerra DOC are judged to be amongst the world's finest.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] In 2012, a bottle of Trebbiano d'Abruzzo ranked No.
[src:burmese-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] IGT wines are Alto Tirino, Colli Aprutini, Colli del Sangro, Colline Frentane, Colline Pescaresi, Colline Teatine, Del Vastese (or Histonium), Terre di Chieti, and Valle Peligna.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine is not very well known in Canada or internationally.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] It has much in common with Québécois cuisine because of its geographical proximity.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] The two often feature the same dishes, but the cuisine of Acadia puts more emphasis on seafood.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine has notably served as the base for Cajun cuisine because the Cajun are descendants of Acadians who were deported to Louisiana.Note 2 It is also believed that Acadians are responsible for normalizing potato consumption in France—a vegetable the French once considered poisonous.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] In the 17th century, French colonists who settled on lands they named Acadia adapted their 16th-century French cuisine to incorporate the crops, seafood and animals that flourished in the region.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Their descendants became the Acadian people and their ingenuity created Acadian cuisine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] After the English conquered Acadia during the 18th century, they decided to deport the Acadians and take their settlements, which were often built on the most fertile earth in the colony.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Most Acadians did not manage to escape the deportation.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] But, of those who did, most fled to the east and north of New BrunswickNote 3.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] As such, Acadian cuisine in the 18th century was refocused around what could be grown, hunted and fished in the less fertile lands of the East Coast of New Brunswick and the Upper St.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine often features fish and seafood, especially cod and Atlantic herring, but also mackerel, berlicoco, lobster, crab, salmon, mussels, trout, clams, flounder, smelt and scallops.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Most fish is consumed fresh, but some are *boucané* (smoked), marinated or salted.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] The most commonly used meat is pork, followed by chicken and beef.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] As with the rest of North America, turkey is commonly consumed during the holidays.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Game like deer, hare, ruffed grouse and moose is consumed regularly in some regions.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Game will replace livestock meat if present and can be given as a gift.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] In some regions, for example Caraquet and the Îles-de-la-Madeleine, more unusual game is or was caught, like seal, bear and seagull.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] The vegetables of Acadian cuisine are the potato, onion, carrot, turnip, legume, beet, squash and corn.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] These vegetables were popular because they were easily preserved for the winter in root cellars and jars.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] The fiddlehead fern was introduced to the Acadians by the indigenous Maliseet, Mi'kmaq and Penobscot peoples in the early 18th Century and remains a popular Acadian dish.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Popular fruits include blueberries, apples, strawberries, raspberries, blackberries, plums, pears and cranberries.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Some ingredients like rice, molasses, dried raisins and brown sugar are part of Acadian cuisine because of historical commerce between Acadia and regions like the Antilles and Brazil.
[src:burmese-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Maple sugar is also a popular sweetener, given the often-close familial ties between Quebec (the world's largest producer of maple sugar) and Acadia.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese cuisine is typified by a wide-ranging array of dishes, including traditional Burmese curries and stews, Burmese salads, accompanied by soups and a medley of vegetables that are traditionally eaten with white rice.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese curries are generally distinguished from other Southeast Asian curries in the former's prominent use of an aromatic trio of garlic, shallots, and ginger (in common with South Asian curries), and the general lack of coconut milk.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese cuisine also features Indian breads as well as noodles, which are fried or prepared in salads and noodle soups, chief among them mohinga.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Street food and snack culture have also nurtured the profuse variety of traditional Burmese fritters and modern savory and sweet snacks labeled under the umbrella of *mont*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Rice is the principal staple in Burmese cuisine, reflecting several millennia of rice cultivation, which first emerged in the country's Chindwin, Ayeyarwady, and Thanlwin river valleys between 11,000 and 5000 BCE.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] By 3000 BCE, irrigated rice cultivation flourished in the region, paralleled by the domestication of cattle and pigs by inhabitants.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] In addition to rice, tea originated in the borderlands separating Myanmar from China, precipitating a longstanding tradition of tea consumption and the development of pickled tea known as *laphet*, which continues to play a pivotal role in Burmese ritual culture.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] This longstanding history is reflected in the Burmese language, which is among the few world languages whose word for "tea" is not etymologically traced back to the Chinese word for "tea" (see etymology of tea).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Agrarian settlements were settled by ancestors of Myanmar's modern-day ethnolinguistic groups.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] From these settlements emerged a succession of Burmese, Mon, Shan, Rakhine-speaking kingdoms and tributary states that now make up contemporary Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Paddy rice cultivation remains synonymous with the predominantly Buddhist Bamar, Mon, Shan, and Rakhine peoples who inhabit the country's fertile lowlands and plateaus.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese cuisine has been significantly enriched by contact and trade with neighboring kingdoms and countries well into modern times.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The Columbian exchange in the 15th and 16th centuries introduced key ingredients into the Burmese culinary repertoire, including tomatoes, chili peppers, peanuts, and potatoes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] A series of Burmese–Siamese wars between the 16th to 19th centuries resulted in the emergence of Thai-inspired delicacies, including *khanon dok*, *shwe yin aye*, *mont let hsaung*, and *Yodaya mont di*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] While record-keeping of pre-colonial culinary traditions is scant, food was and remains deeply intertwined with religious life, especially among Buddhist communities, exemplified in the giving of food alms (dāna), and communal feasts called *satuditha* and *ahlu pwe* (အလှူပွဲ).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] One of the few remaining pre-colonial cookbooks is the *Sadawhset Kyan* (စားတော်ဆက်ကျမ်း, lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] 'Treatise on Royal Foods'), written on a palm leaf manuscript in 1866 during the Konbaung dynasty.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] By the Konbaung dynasty (16th to 19th centuries), elaborate preparations of food played a central role in key court ceremonies (e.g., naming ceremonies, wedding ceremonies, etc.), including as ritual offerings to Hindu and indigenous deities, and as celebratory meals for attendees.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] By the Konbaung period, 126 distinct varieties of rice were cultivated in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] British rule in Burma between the 19th and 20th centuries led to the establishment of Burmese Indian and Sino-Burmese communities that introduced novel cooking techniques, ingredients, food vocabulary, and fusion dishes that are now considered integral parts of Burmese cuisine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] These range from Indian breads such as naan and paratha to Chinese stir frying techniques and ingredients like tofu and soy sauce.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Traditionally, the Burmese eat meals from plates on a low table or *daunglan*, while sitting on a bamboo mat.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Dishes are simultaneously served and shared.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] A traditional meal includes steamed white rice as the main dish accompanied by Burmese curries, a light soup or consommé, and other side dishes, including fried vegetables, Burmese fritters, and *ngapi yay gyo* (ငါးပိရည်ကျို), a plate of fresh and blanched vegetables served with pickled fish dip.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The meal is then finished with a piece of palm sugar or *laphet* (fermented tea leaves).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Out of respect, the eldest diners are always served first before the rest join in; even when the elders are absent, the first morsel of rice from the pot is scooped and put aside as an act of respect to one's parents, a custom known as *u cha* (ဦးချ, lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The Burmese traditionally eat with their right hand, forming the rice into a small ball with only the fingertips and mixing this with various morsels before popping it into their mouths.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Chopsticks and Chinese-style spoons are used for noodle dishes, although noodle salads are more likely to be eaten with just a spoon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Western-style utensils, especially forks and knives, have gained currency in recent years.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] In traditional Burmese eateries, green tea and numerous side dishes are served complimentary alongside the main dishes and rice.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The country's diverse religious makeup influences its cuisine, as Buddhists and Hindus traditionally avoid beef and Muslims pork.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Beef is considered taboo by devout Buddhists and farmers because the cow is highly regarded as a beast of burden.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Vegetarianism is commonly practiced by Buddhists during the three-month Vassa (ဝါတွင်း) between July and October, as well as during Uposatha days, reflected in the Burmese word for "vegetarian," *thet that lut* (သက်သတ်လွတ်, lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] During this time, devout Buddhists observe eight or more precepts, including fasting rules that restrict food intake to two daily meals (i.e., breakfast and lunch) taken before noon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The beef taboo is fairly widespread in Myanmar, particularly in the Buddhist community.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] In Myanmar, beef is typically obtained from cattle that are slaughtered at the end of their working lives (16 years of age) or from sick animals.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Cattle is rarely raised for meat; 58% of cattle in the country is used for draught animal power.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Few people eat beef, and there is a general dislike of beef (especially among the Bamar and Burmese Chinese), although it is more commonly eaten in regional cuisines, particularly those of ethnic minorities like the Kachin.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Buddhists, when giving up meat during the Buddhist (Vassa) or Uposatha days, will forego beef first.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Butchers tend to be Muslim because of the Buddhist doctrine of ahimsa (no harm).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] During the country's last dynasty, the Konbaung dynasty, habitual consumption of beef was punishable by public flogging.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] He subsequently led successful beef boycotts during the colonial era, and influenced a generation of Burmese nationalists in adopting this stance.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] On 29 August 1961, the Burmese Parliament passed the State Religion Promotion Act of 1961, which explicitly banned the slaughtering of cattle nationwide (beef became known as *todo tha* (တိုးတိုးသား); lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Religious groups, such as Muslims, were required to apply for exemption licences to slaughter cattle on religious holidays.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] This ban was repealed a year later, after Ne Win led a coup d'état and declared martial law in the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] In traditional Burmese medicine, foods are divided into two classes: heating (အပူစာ, *apu za*) or cooling (အအေးစာ, *a-aye za*), based on their effects on one's body system, similar to the Chinese classification of food.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Examples of heating foods include chicken, bitter melon, durian, mango, chocolate, and ice cream.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Examples of cooling foods include pork, eggplant, dairy products, cucumbers, and radish.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The Burmese also hold several taboos and superstitions regarding consumption during various occasions in one's life, especially pregnancy.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] For instance, pregnant women are not supposed to eat chili due to the belief that it causes children to have sparse scalp hair.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese dishes are not cooked with precise recipes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The use and portion of ingredients used may vary, but the precision of timing is of utmost importance.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese dishes may be stewed, boiled, fried, roasted, steamed, baked or grilled, or any combination of the said techniques.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese curries use only a handful of spices (in comparison to Indian ones) and use more fresh garlic and ginger.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Broadly speaking, Burmese cuisine is divided between the culinary traditions of Upper Myanmar, which is inland and landlocked; and Lower Myanmar, which is surrounded by numerous rivers, river deltas, and the Andaman Sea.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Variations between regional cuisines are largely driven by the availability of fresh ingredients.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Myanmar's long coastline has provided an abundant source of fresh seafood, which is particularly associated with Rakhine cuisine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Cuisine in Lower Myanmar, including Yangon and Mawlamyaing, makes extensive use of fish and seafood-based products like fish sauce and ngapi (fermented seafood).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The cuisine in Upper Myanmar, including the Bamar heartland (Mandalay, Magway, and Sagaing Regions), Shan State, and Kachin States, tends to use more meat, poultry, pulses and beans.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The level of spices and use of fresh herbs varies depending on the region; Kachin and Shan curries will often use more fresh herbs.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Fusion Chettiar (ချစ်တီးကုလား) cuisine, originating from Southern Indian cuisine, is also popular in cities.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese cuisine incorporates numerous local ingredients that are less frequently used in other Southeast Asian cuisines, among them sour roselle leaves, astringent pennywort leaves, goat, mutton, and dried beans and lentils.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Because a standardised system of romanisation for spoken Burmese does not exist, pronunciations of the following dishes in modern standard Burmese are approximated using IPA, and are provided (see IPA/Burmese for details).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Myanmar is one of very few countries where tea is not only drunk but eaten as lahpet, pickled tea served with various accompaniments.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The practice of eating tea dates in modern-day Myanmar back to prehistoric antiquity, reflecting the legacy of indigenous tribes who pickled and fermented tea leaves inside bamboo tubes, bamboo baskets, plantain leaves and pots.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Tea leaves are traditionally cultivated by the Palaung people.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Pickled tea leaves continue to play an important role in Burmese culture today.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] *Ngapi* (ငါးပိ), a fermented paste made from salted fish or shrimp, is considered the cornerstone of any Burmese traditional meal.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] It is used to season many soups, salads, curries and dishes, and condiments, imparting a rich umami flavor.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The *ngapi* of Rakhine State contains no or little salt, and uses marine fish.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Meanwhile, ngapi made with freshwater fish is common in Ayeyarwady and Tanintharyi regions.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] *Ngapi yay* (ငါးပိရည်) is an essential part of Karen and Bamar cuisine, in which a sauce dip of *ngapi* cooked in various vegetables and spices is served with blanched and fresh vegetables, similar to Thai *nam phrik*, Indonesian *lalab*, and Malay *ulam*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Pickled fish, called *ngachin*, is also used in Burmese cooking.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Shan cuisine traditionally uses fermented beans called *pè ngapi* (ပဲငါးပိ; lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] 'bean *ngapi*'), in lieu of *ngapi*, to impart umami.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] 'spoiled beans') are used as condiments for various Shan dishes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese cuisine also features a wide variety of pickled vegetables and fruits that are preserved in oil and spices, or in brine and rice wine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The former, called *thanat* (သနပ်), are similar to South Asian pickles, including mango pickle.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The latter are called *chinbat* (ချဉ်ဖတ်), and include pickles like *mohnyin gyin*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The most common staple in Myanmar is steamed rice, called *htamin* (ထမင်း).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese varieties of rice are typically starchier than jasmine or basmati rice.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Fragrant, aromatic varieties of white rice, including *paw hsan hmwe* (ပေါ်ဆန်းမွှေး), are popular.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Lower-amylose varieties of glutinous rice, which are called *kauk hnyin* (ကောက်ညှင်း), also feature in Burmese cuisine, including a purple variety called *ngacheik* (ငချိပ်).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Consumers in the northern highlands (e.g., Shan State) prefer stickier, lower-amylose varieties like *kauk hnyin* and *kauk sei*, while consumers in lower delta regions preferring higher-amylose varieties like *kauk chaw* and *kauk kyan*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Lower-amylose varieties of rice are commonly used in traditional Burmese snacks called *mont*.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] While rice is traditionally eaten plain, flavored versions like buttered rice and coconut rice are commonplace festive staples.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese cuisine uses a wide variety of noodles, which are prepared in soups, salads, or other dry noodle dishes and typically eaten outside of lunch or as a snack.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Fresh, thin rice noodles called *mont bat* (မုန့်ဖတ်) or *mont di* (မုန့်တီ), are similar to Thai *khanom chin*, and feature in Myanmar's national dish, mohinga.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese cuisine also has a category of rice noodles of varying sizes and shapes called *nan*, including *nangyi* (နန်းကြီး), thick udon-like noodles; *nanlat* (နန်းလတ်), medium-sized rice noodles; *nanthe* (နန်းသေး), thinner rice noodles; and *nanbya* (နန်းပြား), flat rice noodles.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Cellophane noodles, called *kyazan* (ကြာဆံ, lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] 'lotus thread') and wheat-based noodles called *khauk swe* (ခေါက်ဆွဲ), are often used in salads, soups, and stir-fries.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese salads (အသုပ်; transliterated *athoke* or *athouk*) are a diverse category of indigenous salads in Burmese cuisine.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese salads are made of cooked and raw ingredients that are mixed by hand to combine and balance a wide-ranging array of flavors and textures.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese salads are eaten as standalone snacks, as side dishes paired with Burmese curries, and as entrees.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese curry refers to a diverse array of dishes in Burmese cuisine that consist of protein or vegetables simmered or stewed in an base of aromatics.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese curries generally differ from other Southeast Asian curries (e.g., Thai curry) in that Burmese curries make use of dried spices, in addition to fresh herbs and aromatics, and are often milder.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The most common variety of curry is called *sibyan* (ဆီပြန်; lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] 'oil returns'), which is typified by a layer of oil that separates from the gravy and meat after cooked.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Pork, chicken, goat, shrimp, and fish are commonly prepared in Burmese curries.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] In Burmese cuisine, soups typically accompany meals featuring both rice and noodles, and are paired accordingly to balance contrasting flavors.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Lightly flavored soups, called *hin gyo* (ဟင်းချို) are served with saltier dishes, while sour soups, called *chinyay hin* (ချဉ်ရည်ဟင်း), are paired with rich, fatty Burmese curries.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Indian breads are commonly eaten for breakfast or teatime in Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] *Palata* (ပလာတာ), also known as *htattaya* (ထပ်တစ်ရာ), a flaky fried flatbread related to Indian paratha, is often eaten with curried meats or as dessert with sprinkled sugar, while *nanbya* (နံပြား), a baked flatbread, is eaten with any Indian dishes.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese cuisine has a wide variety of traditional snacks called *mont*, ranging from sweet desserts to savory food items that are steamed, baked, fried, deep-fried, or boiled.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Traditional Burmese fritters, consisting of vegetables or seafood that have been battered and deep-fried, are also eaten as snacks or as toppings.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Myanmar has a wide range of fruits, mostly of tropical origin.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Fruit is commonly eaten as a snack or dessert.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] While most fruits are eaten fresh, a few, including jengkol, are boiled, roasted or otherwise cooked.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Popular fruits include banana, mango, watermelon, papaya, jujube, avocado, pomelo, and guava.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Others include marian plum, mangosteen, sugar-apple, rambutan, durian, jackfruit, lychee, and pomegranate.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Some fruits, including green mangoes, plums, and guavas, are traditionally eaten before they ripen, often mixed with chili powder and salt.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese fruit preserves, called *yo* (ယို), are also commonly eaten as standalone snacks.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Common ones include fruit preserves made from fig, jujube, marian plum, citrus, mango, pineapple, and durian.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] 300 cultivars of mango are grown in Myanmar, including *seintalon* (စိန်တစ်လုံး, lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Tea is the national drink of Myanmar, reflecting the influence of Buddhism and its views on temperance.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Tea is central to Burmese dining culture; complimentary green tea is customarily served to diners at restaurants and teashops alike.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Various liquid concoctions made from fruits and coconut milk, including sugarcane juice, and *mont let hsaung* (မုန့်လက်ဆောင်း) are also popular.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Indigenous fermented drinks like palm wine are also found across the country.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] During a traditional Burmese meal, drinks are not often served; instead, the usual liquid refreshment is a light broth or consommé served from a communal bowl.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Plain green tea, *yay nway gyan* (ရေနွေးကြမ်း, lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] 'crude tea water'), is a popular form of tea drunk in Myanmar.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Tea leaves are traditionally cultivated in Shan State and Kachin State.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Milk tea, called *laphet yay cho* (လက်ဖက်ရည်ချို), made with strongly brewed black tea leaves, and sweetened with a customized ratio of condensed milk and evaporated milk, is also popular.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Palm wine, called *htan yay* (ထန်းရည်), made from the fermented sap of the toddy palm, is traditionally consumed in rural parts of Upper Myanmar Ethnic communities, including the Kachin and Shan, also brew local moonshines.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Several ethnic minorities traditionally brew alcoholic beverages using rice or glutinous rice called khaung (ခေါင်ရည်).
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The *khaung* of the Chin peoples is brewed using millet seeds.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Locally brewed beers include Irrawaddy, Mandalay, Myanmar, and Tiger.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Dine-in restaurants that serve steamed rice with traditional Burmese curries and dishes are called *htamin hsaing* (ထမင်းဆိုင်; lit.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] At traditional curry shops, soup is typically served complimentary, alongside pickled and raw vegetables, chutneys and various seasonings.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Tea shops are prevalent across the country, forming an important part of communal life.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Typically open throughout the day, some Burmese tea shops cater to locals, long-distance drivers and travellers alike.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] The Burmese typically gather in tea shops to drink milk tea served with an extensive array of snacks and meals.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Street food stalls and hawkers are a feature of the Burmese urban landscape, especially in major cities like Yangon.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Burmese salads, snacks, and fritters are especially popular street foods.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] In recent years, some major cities have clamped down on street food vendors.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] In 2016, Yangon banned the city's 6,000 street vendors from selling food on major thoroughfares, and relocated them to formal night markets set up by the city.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Night markets, called *nya zay* (ညဈေး), are a feature of many Burmese towns and cities.
[src:burmese-cuisine/burmese-cuisine] Colonial observers as early as 1878 noted Burmese street hawkers selling delicacies, such as fruits, cakes, and laphet during "night bazaars." The streets surrounding major daytime markets, such as Zegyo Market in Mandalay, typically double as makeshift night markets during the evenings.
